<subSubSection pageId="21" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[264,1324,283,830]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[312,451,644,670]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Discussion.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[463,719,644,669]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Schinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufocostulata">
<emphasis box="[463,719,644,669]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">Schinia rufocostulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is known only from the 
<typeStatus box="[1036,1087,644,670]" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">type</typeStatus>
locality of Dugout Wells, in Big Bend National Park, Brewster Co., Texas. The apical area of the forewing is distinct in 
<taxonomicName box="[391,547,724,749]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Schinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rufocostulata">
<emphasis box="[391,547,724,749]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">rufocostulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by having the rufous color of the terminal band extending down costa almost to the median band. This character is lacking in 
<taxonomicName box="[987,1062,764,789]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Schinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ciliata">
<emphasis box="[987,1062,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">ciliata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The specimens show no variation in the median band color as in 
<taxonomicName box="[773,848,804,829]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Schinia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ciliata">
<emphasis box="[773,848,804,829]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="22">ciliata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
